==使用概述==
'''code1, 2, 3, ..., 20'''. Letter definitions to be translated to a braille cell (case insensitive, A=a). Only the first unnamed parameter is evaluated when this template is substituted, and only [[#Braille cell definitions (dot numbering)|dot patterns]] in numeric order are valid input.

'''[[#lang|lang]]''' for the ''braille language''. Four braille languages are recognised: [[Grade 2 braille|English (grade 2)]], [[French Braille|French]], [[Japanese braille|Japanese]] and [[Korean braille|Korean]] braille. English (grade 2) braille is default so doesn't have to be entered, the other languages should be defined (e.g. {{code|1=<nowiki>lang=Japanese</nowiki>}}).

[[Template:Braille cell/types|'''type''']]. Type of braille cell to be shown: 6-dot cell image, 8-dot cell image, in-line text character {{code|1=6, 6dot, 8, 8dot, image, text}}. The default is text (inline font character). For Japanese and Korean braille script, entering {{code|1=<nowiki>type=Korean</nowiki>}} produces illustrative colored braille cells (see [[Korean braille]]). These two types are default for their languages.

'''[[#size|size]]'''. Width size of the image (in {{code|1=px}}) of font-size of the inline text (like %, em, px). Add the unit to the number (e.g. {{code|1=<nowiki>size=20px</nowiki>}} for 6dot/8dot images, and {{code|1=10px, 2em, 150%}} for fontsize).

'''[[#caption|caption]]'''. A descriptive caption (mouse hover text) for a braille character is added. It can be shortened to the simple definition ({{code|1=caption=}} (&lt;blank>), and be hidden ({{code|1=caption=no}}).

'''[[#background|background]]''' or '''bg'''. Sets the background color. For {{code|1=type=text}} only. Default is {{code|1=#f4f4f4}}. Examples:
* {{tlx|Braille cell|<nowiki>K|L|M|type=text</nowiki>}} &rarr; {{Braille cell|K|L|M|type=text}}
* {{tlx|Braille cell|<nowiki>K|L|M|type=text|background=yellow</nowiki>}} &rarr; {{Braille cell|K|L|M|type=text|background=yellow}}
* {{tlx|Braille cell|<nowiki>K|L|M|type=text|background=transparent</nowiki>}} &rarr; {{Braille cell|K|L|M|type=text|background=transparent}}

==輸入值==
Possible input: plain text and various braille cell definitions (see below). Up to 20 cells can be indicated in a single call to the template, each dot pattern separated with a pipe character "|". Skipping a code is read as a blank cell (e.g. {{code|1=<nowiki>{{braille cell|A||b|o|o|k</nowiki>}} introduces a blank cell after "A").
All defined input values will output a single [[Braille]] cell.

Acceptable input values to produce braille cells are of the following types:

===字母===
''簡單英文字母'' - 大寫或小寫："A", "c", "X", "W", "z", 等。6點，8點，及日本型式單元均有效。

''Accented French letters'' - capital or lower case: "È", "Ö", "å", etc.

''Double letters and words'' - capital or lower case: "st", "SH", "for", "Th", "ing", etc.

''Japanese letters'' - [[Katakana]], [[hiragana]], and Japanese diacritics (e.g. "dakuten", "chōon", "-Y-", etc.) are valid input for 6-dot, 8-dot, text, and Japanese cell types, with [[Romaji]] valid for Japanese cells only.

''Korean letters'' - The {{tla|Unicode chart Hangul Jamo|positional Hangul jamo}} are valid input for 6-dot, 8-dot, text, and Korean cell types, with Revised Romanization (X- for initial, -X for final consonants) valid for Korean cells only.

===其它字型===
''數字'' - 以數字符號為前綴："#0" (="J"), "#7" (="G")等。

''Punctuation'' - signs or names: "exclamation", ".", "openquote", "bracket", etc.

''Other symbols'' - "null" or "blank", "accent" or "`", "contraction" or "contr2", "capital", "decimal", "contr3" or "space" (dots 4+5), "correction", "cursive" or "contr1", "number" or "#".

'''Notes''' - For the question mark "?" in French, use {{code|1=lang=French}}. Otherwise it will produce (default) the English braille. The French "space" is the third English Braille contraction prefix, while English Braille space is "blank" or "null", and French "cursive" is the first English Braille contractions prefix.

=== 盲文單元定義（點編號）===
[[File:Braille8dotCellNumbering.svg|thumb|right|60px|8-dot [[Braille]] cell dot numbers. Dots 7 and 8 are not found on a 6-dot Braille cell.]]
Four options can be used in this Braille cell template to produce a cell, and all are case-insensitive (A=a).
* {{tlx|braille cell|type=text|1234|1423|⠏|U+280F||u+280f}} &rarr; {{braille cell|type=text|1234|1423|⠏|U+280F|u+280f}}
Note that this cell definition is unrelated to any language (no "A" assigned).

A braille cell is defined by '''naming the raised dots'''. In 6-dot notation there are 64 combinations, in 8-dot notation this number is 256 (including all 6-dot cells). Such a definition is ''independent'' of the braille language (there is no connection with a letter ''A''; this is for the Braille language to add).

Using the cell numbering shown here, one can simply mention the raised dots: say dots-1234 for {{braille cell|type=text|1234}}. The numeric order can be in raising numeric order ("123456"), or in row-by-row order ("142536"), so the same cell is uniquely identified by {{code|1=1234}} or by {{code|1423}}. A dot pattern in rising numeric order is the only valid input when [[WP:Substitution|substituting]] this template.

Another identification is the Unicode character, ⠏, that is {{unichar|280F|Braille pattern dots-1234|html=|note=block: [[Braille Patterns (Unicode)|Braille Patterns]]}}. The block has a mapping from raised dots to character id in the range U+28xx.

Inversely, a cell can be defined by its Unicode character id: U+280F defines cell with raised dots-1234.
